snippet.textDisplay: Learning Excel macros ie; VBA (Visual Basic for Applications) is the perfect way for a person to get into actual programming. I’d suggest transitioning from VBA into Visual Basic .NET then you can learn something like ASP.NET to build Web applications using the Visual Basic language, then once you have a firm grasp of the .NET framework and are comfortable using the Visual Studio IDE for development, I would recommend moving to a language that's more commonly used in the industry, C#. It is one of the common languages that run on the dot net framework and Visual Studio will be your IDE of choice still so the shift will be mostly focused around syntax differences and slightly different coding styles and conventions between the two languages. Most importantly though, any libraries you may have written in VB can be called from your C# code and vice versa, that's the beauty of the dot net framework. So your old code won't go to waste.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey Mike, love your videos. I'm just here to add an important note, which I didn't find anyone mention in comment section. Bump starting a car with gasoline engine like you showed is totally ok, but it is not very easy or good to do with diesel engine. Diesel engines are using glow plugs to preheat a mixture of gas to start an ignition, with a dead battery you don't have the mixture in cylinders preheated by glow plugs and it's almost impossible to bump start like that, especially on a cold day. I'm not a mechanic, but I also know that trying to start diesel engine without preheating is not very healthy for cars with diesel engines.
